[src:sequence-alignment-dp/dynamic-programming] This functional equation is known as the Bellman equation, which can be solved for an exact solution of the discrete approximation of the optimization equation.
[src:sequence-alignment-dp/dynamic-programming] In economics, the objective is generally to maximize (rather than minimize) some dynamic social welfare function.
[src:sequence-alignment-dp/dynamic-programming] In Ramsey's problem, this function relates amounts of consumption to levels of utility.
[src:sequence-alignment-dp/dynamic-programming] Loosely speaking, the planner faces the trade-off between contemporaneous consumption and future consumption (via investment in capital stock that is used in production), known as intertemporal choice.
[src:sequence-alignment-dp/dynamic-programming] Future consumption is discounted at a constant rate $\beta \in (0,1)$ .
[src:sequence-alignment-dp/dynamic-programming] where c is consumption, k is capital, and f is a production function satisfying the Inada conditions.
[src:sequence-alignment-dp/dynamic-programming] An initial capital stock $k_{0}>0$ is assumed.
[src:sequence-alignment-dp/dynamic-programming] Let $c_{t}$ be consumption in period t, and assume consumption yields utility $u(c_{t})=\ln(c_{t})$ as long as the consumer lives.
[src:sequence-alignment-dp/dynamic-programming] Assume the consumer is impatient, so that he discounts future utility by a factor b each period, where $0<b<1$ .
[src:sequence-alignment-dp/dynamic-programming] Assume initial capital is a given amount $k_{0}>0$ , and suppose that this period's capital and consumption determine next period's capital as $k_{t+1}=Ak_{t}^{a}-c_{t}$ , where A is a positive constant and $0<a<1$ .
[src:sequence-alignment-dp/dynamic-programming] Written this way, the problem looks complicated, because it involves solving for all the choice variables $c_{0},c_{1},c_{2},\ldots ,c_{T}$ .
[src:sequence-alignment-dp/dynamic-programming] The dynamic programming approach to solve this problem involves breaking it apart into a sequence of smaller decisions.
[src:sequence-alignment-dp/dynamic-programming] To do so, we define a sequence of *value functions* $V_{t}(k)$ , for $t=0,1,2,\ldots ,T,T+1$ which represent the value of having any amount of capital k at each time t.
[src:sequence-alignment-dp/dynamic-programming] There is (by assumption) no utility from having capital after death, $V_{T+1}(k)=0$ .
[src:sequence-alignment-dp/dynamic-programming] The value of any quantity of capital at any previous time can be calculated by backward induction using the Bellman equation.
[src:sequence-alignment-dp/dynamic-programming] This problem is much simpler than the one we wrote down before, because it involves only two decision variables, $c_{t}$ and $k_{t+1}$ .
[src:sequence-alignment-dp/dynamic-programming] Intuitively, instead of choosing his whole lifetime plan at birth, the consumer can take things one step at a time.
[src:sequence-alignment-dp/dynamic-programming] At time t, his current capital $k_{t}$ is given, and he only needs to choose current consumption $c_{t}$ and saving $k_{t+1}$ .
[src:sequence-alignment-dp/dynamic-programming] To actually solve this problem, we work backwards.
[src:sequence-alignment-dp/dynamic-programming] For simplicity, the current level of capital is denoted as k. $V_{T+1}(k)$ is already known, so using the Bellman equation once we can calculate $V_{T}(k)$ , and so on until we get to $V_{0}(k)$ , which is the *value* of the initial decision problem for the whole lifetime.
[src:sequence-alignment-dp/dynamic-programming] We see that it is optimal to consume a larger fraction of current wealth as one gets older, finally consuming all remaining wealth in period T, the last period of life.
[src:sequence-alignment-dp/dynamic-programming] There are two key attributes that a problem must have in order for dynamic programming to be applicable: optimal substructure and overlapping sub-problems.
[src:sequence-alignment-dp/dynamic-programming] If a problem can be solved by combining optimal solutions to *non-overlapping* sub-problems, the strategy is called "divide and conquer" instead.
[src:sequence-alignment-dp/dynamic-programming] This is why merge sort and quick sort are not classified as dynamic programming problems.
